From b77c96a028ea9633898c4a643c60e62cb1fd6a3d Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: souliane <21343492+souliane@users.noreply.github.com>
Date: Fri, 26 Jun 2026 16:13:05 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 2/2] fix(dream): count distinct tokens for the cold-recall
 relevance floor (#2746)
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Adversarial review of the cold-tier RECALL follow-up flagged a relevance-floor
bug: _score summed the entry-token overlap (which already includes name tokens)
AND the name-token overlap, so a single filename-token match double-counted to 2
and fake-cleared the floor of 2 — surfacing an otherwise-irrelevant rule on one
incidental topic word. The floor now counts DISTINCT matched tokens across the
entry; the name-token weight is applied only POST-floor for ranking.

Review nits folded in:
- renamed-file dedup compares a prefix bounded just under the hot summary clip,
  so a long cold signature clipped in the hot index is still recognised as
  already loaded (a verbatim substring check missed it)
- gates._signature_line imports reindex at module level (reindex is stdlib-only,
  imports neither gates nor decay; no cycle), dropping the lazy-import noqa
- handle_recall_cold_memory wraps its whole body (kill-switch read and dir
  resolution included) so a misbehaving reader on a hostile payload can never
  traceback out of the UserPromptSubmit leaf
- reindex module docstring now describes the metadata-skip and BINDING fallback
- ambient-strip carries a comment documenting the unterminated-open-tag
  truncate-to-end trade-off

Tests: a regression test proves a single name-token-only overlap returns no hit
(observed RED before the floor fix, GREEN after), plus the clipped-signature
dedup guard, an exact RECALL_LIMIT cap, and an isolated +3 BINDING-boost ranking
test where a lower-base BINDING entry outranks a higher-base plain entry.
